summary.seg: This 16th-century manuscript is a late copy of Achilles Tatius, The Adventures of Leucippe and Clitophon , one of the few surviving Ancient Greek romances and the only extant work of Tatius who lived and worked in Alexandria in the written in the 2nd century. The manuscript was copied from the editio princeps of the work, printed in Heidelberg in 1601 from a 16th-century manuscript of the Bibliotheca Palatina, now in the Vatican (Vatican City, Bibliotheca Apostolica Vaticana, Pal. gr. 52).

list.item: Book viii: ff. 64r-70v: there is lacuna from viii 16, 3 (f. 79v ἀποσκευάσαντες ἔρριψαν ὁμοίως) to viii 17, 4 (f. 80r ἦν δὲ καὶ ὀφθῆναι καλὸς) indicated on upper margin of f. 80r (Λείπει τὰ ἑξῆς τοῦ τῶν τῆς φάρου λῃστῶν μύθου, καὶ τὰ ἄλλα); the same lacuna is in the editio princeps, in which the last part is taken from the manuscripts Vatican City, Bibliotheca Apostolica Vaticana, Vat. gr. 2367 or Paris, Bibliothèque nationale de France, grec 2913

support.material:
Western paper, folded in quarto. Watermark: pillars in the gutter comparable to Heawood, Watermarks mainly of the 17th and 18th centuries (Monumenta Chartae Papyraceae I) 3506
; watermarks of this shape are in use in the first half of 17th century.

supportDesc.foliation: i-ix + 1-82, [83], 84-90, [91-95], 96-97. Modern foliation in Roman and Arabic numerals in the top right-hand corner, recto, in pencil (i-ix, 82-97) and brown ink (1-81).

collation.p: The manuscript consistes of 13 quaternions: quires 1-138.
collation.catchwords: Horizontal catchwords by the same of the text on each folio. Some of them are lost in trimming.

supportDesc.condition: In generally good condition; folios are yellowed by time and stained; ff. iii-iv and 90-91 are partially uncut, with small tears: ff. iii verso, iv recto, 90v and 91r not imaged.

layoutDesc.layout: ff. 1r-81r: A single column of 31 lines. 190 117

handNote.p: The manuscript is written by a western hand of the first half of the 17th century in a mixed minuscule; title are in majuscule. Abbreviations and ligatures are absent. The writing is characterized by an inclined gamma, mu traced from a u with the addition of a hook, and psi traced in four strokes.

binding.p: Binding in brown leather covering over couched-laminate boards. On the spine a general title is tooled in gold: Liber Græ.

history.origin: The watermark, the handwriting features and filiation from the printed edition suggest that the manuscript was written in the first half of 17th century.
history.provenance: Owned by John Moore (1646-1714), bishop of Ely Moore, John, 1646-1714 : number 219 of Bernard, Catalogi librorum manuscriptorum Angliæ et Hiberniæ (1697).
history.acquisition: Presented to the University Library in 1715 by George I George I, King of Great Britain, 1660-1727 . The royal bookplate engraved by John Pine (1690-1756) in 1736 remains on the pastedown.

recordHist.source: Description (2019) draws on A catalogue of the Manuscripts preserved in the Library of the University of Cambridge, vol. 3, Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, 1858, p. 234.
